  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A large share of the wealth held by Brisbane homeowners in their late sixties and seventies is locked up in the family home. Many of these homes were bought decades ago for a fraction of what they are worth today, and the equity has quietly grown into the single largest asset on the household balance sheet. When retirement income no longer comfortably covers living costs, medical expenses, or the things that make retirement worthwhile, that equity becomes hard to ignore. Two main paths exist to access it: a reverse mortgage, which lets you borrow against the home and stay living in it, or selling the property outright and using the proceeds to fund a new chapter. Both are legitimate. Both come with trade-offs that are not always obvious until years later.</p>

      <p>The right answer depends on your specific circumstances: your health, your family situation, what you actually want from the next fifteen or twenty years, and the shape of your estate. This article is not financial advice, and anyone considering either path should consult a qualified financial adviser and, ideally, a solicitor who specialises in elder law. What we can offer is a clear-eyed look at how each option tends to play out for Brisbane homeowners, drawn from the patterns we see again and again in the inner east.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How a reverse mortgage actually works</h2>
      <p>A reverse mortgage is a loan secured against your home. You do not make repayments while you live there. The interest compounds each month and is added to the loan balance, which is repaid from the sale of the property when you move into aged care, pass away, or voluntarily sell. In Australia, reverse mortgages are regulated under the National Consumer Credit Protection Act, and since 2012 they have included a statutory no-negative-equity guarantee: you or your estate will never owe more than the home is worth at the time it is sold.</p>

      <p>The amount you can borrow depends on your age and the value of your property. A 65 year old might be able to access roughly 15 to 20 percent of the home's value; by age 80 that can rise to 30 percent or more. On a Brisbane inner-east home worth $1.6 million, that could mean anywhere from $240,000 to $480,000 in available credit depending on the lender and your age. You can draw it as a lump sum, a regular income stream, a line of credit, or a combination. The flexibility is part of the appeal.</p>

      <p>The catch is the compounding. Interest rates on reverse mortgages in Australia are typically 2 to 3 percentage points higher than standard variable home loans, and because interest capitalises, the balance grows quickly. A $300,000 reverse mortgage at 8.5 percent, with no repayments, roughly doubles every nine years. After 15 years, that $300,000 has compounded to around $900,000. If the home has appreciated at a similar pace, the net equity may be preserved. If it has not, the estate left to beneficiaries can be materially smaller than expected.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What selling and downsizing looks like in practice</h2>
      <p>Selling the family home and moving into something smaller, simpler, or closer to family is the more traditional path, and in the Brisbane inner east it often makes strong financial sense. A three or four bedroom Queenslander in Camp Hill, Coorparoo, or Morningside that is worth $1.6 million today can be sold, replaced with a well-located two bedroom apartment or low-maintenance villa for $700,000 to $900,000, and leave the owner with $500,000 to $800,000 in cash after transaction costs and stamp duty on the new property.</p>

      <p>Those proceeds sit in your name, earn investment returns if managed sensibly, and are fully within your control. You can draw on them as income, contribute to super under the downsizer contribution scheme (available to Australians aged 55 and over for the sale of a home held for at least 10 years, up to $300,000 per person), or simply keep them as a buffer for future medical or care costs. Compared to a compounding loan balance, the clarity is considerable.</p>

      <p>The trade-offs are not only financial. Leaving a home you have lived in for 20 or 30 years is genuinely hard. Neighbours, routines, the garden, the room that used to be a child's bedroom, the memory of Christmas lunches on the back deck: these are not line items on a spreadsheet, but they are real. Any honest conversation about downsizing has to sit with that reality rather than treat the home as a pure financial asset.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The financial comparison, honestly</h2>
      <p>On pure numbers, selling and downsizing almost always leaves the homeowner (and their estate) better off than a reverse mortgage, provided the new home genuinely costs significantly less than the old one. The reason is the difference between compounding debt and preserved equity. A reverse mortgage turns equity into cash at a real cost of 8 to 10 percent per year in compounded interest. A downsize turns equity into cash at a one-off cost of around 5 to 7 percent of the sale price (agent fees, marketing, conveyancing, moving costs) plus the stamp duty on the new purchase.</p>

      <p>Over 10 to 15 years, that difference can easily amount to hundreds of thousands of dollars. For an estate that matters to children or grandchildren, this is a significant consideration. For a homeowner who explicitly does not intend to leave an inheritance and values staying in the family home above all other factors, it may be an acceptable cost.</p>

      <p>Reverse mortgages also carry a subtler risk: they reduce the flexibility of the home as a future asset. If your health deteriorates and you need to sell and move into aged care, the accumulated loan balance is deducted from the sale proceeds first. If those proceeds were going to fund a Refundable Accommodation Deposit (RAD) at a residential aged care facility, the available capital can be meaningfully lower than expected. Plan for the move you might need in 10 years, not just the one you want today.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When a reverse mortgage is the right call</h2>
      <p>There are situations where a reverse mortgage is genuinely the better choice. Chief among them: when the homeowner's strong preference is to age in place, the home is well-suited to that (single level, close to services, manageable to maintain), and the amount needed is modest. Drawing $100,000 to cover a kitchen renovation, medical costs, or a buffer for occasional travel, from a home worth $1.5 million, will not materially damage the estate even over a 15 year horizon. The compounding is meaningful but contained.</p>

      <p>It can also make sense where the family situation is such that inheritance is not a priority, where the spouse's health makes a move impractical or distressing, or where the homeowner has exhausted other options. The statutory no-negative-equity guarantee means you cannot owe more than the house is worth, which puts a floor under the downside even in unusual scenarios.</p>

      <p>Where it tends to go wrong is when a reverse mortgage is used to fund ongoing shortfalls in living costs over a long period, or as a way to avoid a decision that eventually has to be made anyway. Drawing $30,000 a year for 15 years at compounding interest can consume most of the equity in the home, leaving limited options when aged care costs arrive. The flexibility can be a trap if it is used to defer rather than solve.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When selling is clearly the better path</h2>
      <p>Selling tends to be the right call when the current home no longer suits how you want to live. Too many stairs, a garden that has become a burden, rooms that sit empty, a suburb that has drifted away from family and medical services: these are signals that the home is working against you, not for you. In that situation, accessing equity through a reverse mortgage just funds continued occupation of a home that is no longer the right fit. Selling resets the situation completely.</p>

      <p>It is also usually the better path when a larger amount of capital is needed (more than 10 to 15 percent of the home's value), when the homeowner intends to preserve the estate for beneficiaries, when long-term aged care is foreseeable within 10 years, or when the opportunity to contribute to super under the downsizer scheme is available. On this last point, a couple selling a home owned for more than 10 years can contribute up to $600,000 combined to super, tax-free, even if they have already reached their normal contribution caps. Used well, this alone can materially improve retirement income.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The inner-east Brisbane context</h2>
      <p>There is a specific reason this decision comes up so often in Coorparoo, Camp Hill, Morningside, Hawthorne, and Norman Park. Many homeowners in their late sixties and seventies bought their homes when these suburbs were middle-class family areas with median prices in the low hundreds of thousands. Those same homes, after 25 to 35 years of appreciation and the transformation of the inner east into one of Brisbane's most desirable precincts, are now worth $1.4 million to $2.2 million. The pension position of the household has often not changed nearly as much as the house value.</p>

      <p>This is a good problem to have, but it does need to be actively managed. Doing nothing is a decision in itself, and one that gradually locks more and more of your wealth into an illiquid asset while your income stays fixed. Whether the right answer is a reverse mortgage or a downsize depends on the specific circumstances, but the one choice that tends to age poorly is postponing the conversation until health, circumstances, or family dynamics force a rushed decision.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A framework for making the call</h2>
      <p>Work through four questions with a financial adviser who understands retirement income streams, not just accumulation. First: does your current home genuinely suit how you want to live for the next 10 years, or are you simply used to it? Second: how much capital do you actually need, and over what period? Third: what matters to you about the estate you leave, and what matters to the people you would be leaving it to? Fourth: what happens if your health changes in the next five years, and does your current plan cope with that scenario?</p>

      <p>If your home suits you, your capital need is modest, estate preservation is not a priority, and your health is stable, a reverse mortgage can be a reasonable tool. If any of those conditions are soft, a downsize deserves serious consideration. For many inner-east homeowners, the conversation ends up being less about which option is financially optimal and more about what kind of life you want to live for the years that are left. That is a better framing than the product comparison alone.</p>

